Assessment of a Potential Velocity Barrier for Adult Steelhead Migration on the South Fork Clearwater River - Preliminary

Michael W. Ackerman1,✉, and Ryan N. Kinzer1

06 February, 2024

1 Nez Perce Tribe, Department of Fisheries Resources Management, 14054 Burr Dr., McCall, Idaho, 83638, USA

✉ Correspondence: Michael W. Ackerman <mikea@nezperce.org>

1 Background

A section of the South Fork Clearwater River near milepost (MP) 28 has been considered a potential barrier to adult steelhead migration due to high water velocities, at least during some flows. These high water velocities are hypothesized to hinder, or periodically prevent, some adult steelhead from migrating upstream of the barrier, limiting their use of available spawning habitat upstream of the high-velocity section in the mainsteam South Fork Clearwater River and its tributaries. Namely, previous work has indicated that stream velocities within the section likely impede upstream passage for adult steelhead at flows greater than approximately 1,000 cfs (~600 cfs at the previous Elk City gage) (Timm et al., 2018, 2017).

This document provides a preliminary assessment of adult steelhead passage at the putative velocity barrier (hereafter barrier) based on detections of PIT-tagged adults in the South Fork Clearwater River, including at sites SC3 and SC4 located downstream and upstream of the barrier, respectively. PIT-tagged individuals include adults newly tagged at Lower Granite Dam and individuals tagged and released as juveniles at various locations including within the South Fork Clearwater River. In particular, we’re interested in whether returning PIT-tagged adult observations suggest that adults passing SC3 “convert” to locations upstream of the barrier (e.g., SC4) at rates lower than expected, suggesting that the barrier hinders or prevents passage at least for some adults. Although the evaluation is focused on steelhead, we include data from PIT-tagged adult Chinook salmon for comparison.

1.1 Study area

The section of river considered to be a potential velocity barrier is located on river kilometer (rkm) 71 of the South Fork Clearwater River (Figure 1.1). Figure 1.1 and Table 1.1 additionally show each of the instream PIT tag detection sites (IPTDS) used in the evaluation which detect adult steelhead and Chinook salmon, including their rkm from the mouth of the South Fork Clearwater River.

Figure 1.1: Map of the study area including the locations of each instream PIT tag detection system and the approximate location of the potential velocity barrier shown in red.

2 Evaluation

2.1 Data

Our evaluation used information from PIT-tagged adult steelhead and Chinook salmon detected at any IPTDS in the South Fork Clearwater River during their upstream migration to spawn. First, we queried DART to identify all PIT tags observed at Lower Granite Dam for steelhead and Chinook salmon, during spawn years 2022 and 2023, using the queryObsDART() function in the R package PITcleanr, and filtered those observations to identify any returning adult later observed at any IPTDS in the South Fork Clearwater River (Table 1.1). Note that adult detection rates on the Lower Granite Dam adult fish ladder are essentially 100%, and thus, any PIT-tagged adult returning to the South Fork Clearwater River is expected to not be “missed”. We then used the PIT-tag lists of returning adults to the South Fork Clearwater River and queried their complete tag histories in PTAGIS which includes their mark and release information, plus any observations, for subsequent analyses. The complete tag histories were then “compressed” and “filtered” using the compress() and filterDetections() functions in PITcleanr, respectively. For steelhead, we removed any detections after May 31 during the spawn year and for Chinook salmon after September 15 to avoid detections of any kelts, shed tags, etc. The compressed and filtered detections for steelhead and Chinook salmon for spawn years 2022 and 2023 are available for download here. The filtered detections were also converted to capture histories using the buildCapHist() function in PITcleanr. Finally, biological and origin (e.g., natural- versus hatchery-origin) information for each tag were pulled from the Lower Granite Dam trapping database (LGTrappingDB). All data and code used in this evaluation are available at a GitHub site here.

2.2 Conversion Rates

First, we estimated conversion rates to each IPTDS for Chinook salmon and steelhead in spawn years 2022 and 2023 (Table 2.1). The conversion rate provides an estimate of the percentage of PIT-tagged adults that arrive at a given site of those that passed the previous site. For example, in SY2023, we estimated that 12 PIT-tagged steelhead passed SC4, which is 15.6% of the 77 PIT-tagged steelhead estimated to have passed SC3. Table 2.1 provides the number of tags observed at each IPTDS, plus estimates of detection efficiencies, expanded (estimated) tags, and conversion rates to each by species and spawn year.

Conversion rates to SC3 and SC4, within each species, were similar in both spawn years 2022 and 2023 (Figure 2.1), suggesting that adults had a similar probability of passing to SC4 as to SC3; although conversion rates for Chinook salmon were much higher than for steelhead.

Figure 2.1: Conversion rates for Chinook salmon and steelhead to sites SC3 and SC4 on the South Fork Clearwater River. Conversion rate represents the percentage of tagged fish estimated to have arrived at the site of those that passed the previous site downstream.

2.3 Length and Saltwater Age

Next, we summarized conversion rates by fork length (mm) and saltwater age for PIT-tagged adults observed at SC3 and SC4. In particular, we were interested in the percentage of tags at SC3 that were later detected at SC4. If the barrier reach was problematic to adult passage due to high water velocities, we might anticipate that larger or older fish convert at higher rates due to increased fitness or swimming capabilities. Observed tags at SC3 and SC4 were converted to estimates of tags passing each array based on year- and species-specific detection probabilities (Table 2.1). Sample sizes are low, but no noticeable trends were observed in conversion rates by length or saltwater age (Tables 2.2 and 2.3).

Additionally, we summarized the fork lengths of PIT-tagged adults that arrived at SC4 (TRUE) versus those observed at SC3, but did not arrive at SC4 (FALSE; Figure 2.3). Again, we might hypothesize that adults arriving to SC4 are larger than those that did not arrive if water velocities were problematic for smaller or younger fish.

2.4 Flow

We summarized conversion rates by water level (m) recorded at SC4 using the IPTDS environmental probe (Table 2.4). It is worth noting that above a water level of 0.8 m, only 1 of 23 steelhead that passed SC3 arrived at SC4; however, sample sizes at higher water levels are low and nearly all Chinook salmon that passed SC3 arrived at SC4 at similar water levels. For this analysis, the water level recorded for each fish was the water level at SC4 when that fish was most recently observed at a site downstream of the barrier reach.

2.5 Release Group

Finally, we also considered release groups when evaluating conversion rates through the high-velocity reach; adults that return from juvenile releases downstream of the reach may not have the propensity to migrate through the reach. In other words, we are primarily interested in adults returning from juvenile releases upstream of the high-velocity reach to compare passage to SC4 relative to downstream reaches. Table @ref(tab:release groups) shows that among adult Chinook salmon and steelhead returning to the South Fork Clearwater River in spawn years 2022 and 2023, only 22 steelhead were from a juvenile release upstream near Newsome Creek (NEWSOC). Of those 22 steelhead adults, 11 (50.0%) were observed at SC3 of which 3 (27.2%) were observed migrating through the high-velocity reach and arrived at SC4 (Table 2.7).

3 Discussion

Based on adult returns in spawn years 2022 and 2023, it is difficult to discern whether the high-velocity reach hinders or prevents upstream passage for steelhead. Conversion rates to SC4 from SC3 were 13.9% and 15.6% for adult in spawn years 2022 and 2023, respectively; however, those rates are not considerable different that conversion rates of 29.3% and 13.4% to SC3 from SC2 (Table 2.1). Very few adult steelhead were observed migrating to SC4 during higher flows (Table 2.5), but sample sizes are low. Moreover, very few adults from juvenile releases upstream of the high-velocity reach were available for our evaluation.

Juvenile steelhead were released in Newsome Creek in spring 2022; 1-ocean adults from those releases will return to the South Fork Clearwater River in spring 2024 and 2-ocean adults in spring 2025. Those returning adults should provide a more thorough evaluation of passage through the high-velocity reach.
